<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title> COMPLAINT Breast swelling case sheet part</title>
    <link id="light-styles" rel="stylesheet" href="Case_sheet_styles.css">
    <link id="dark-styles" rel="alternate stylesheet" title="dark" href="Case_sheet_styles_dark.css">
  </head>
  <body> <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode">🌙 Dark Mode</button>
    <summary class="h4">1<sup>ST</sup> COMPLAINT: SWELLING/LUMP IN RIGHT BREAST
      (for 2 months)</summary>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>S: Site</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Which breast? (</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Right/Left/</li>
            <li>Bilateral)</li>
          </ul>
          <li>Specific quadrant? (e.g., </li>
          <ul>
            <li>Upper Outer Quadrant, </li>
            <li>Upper Inner, </li>
            <li>Lower Outer, </li>
            <li>Lower Inner, </li>
            <li>Central/Retroareolar)</li>
          </ul>
          <li> lump in <em>axilla</em>?</li>
          <li>Where did patient first notice it precisely?</li>
          <li>Any relation to <strong>previous </strong>burn, <strong>scar</strong>,
            pin prick, or naevus.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>O: Onset</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Was the onset gradual or sudden?</li>
          <li>Any history of trauma to the breast? (Can lead to: 1. Hematoma, 2.
            Fat necrosis)</li>
          <li>Was it noticed incidentally, during self-examination, or by a
            partner/doctor?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>D: Duration</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>When did patient first notice the lump/swelling? (e.g., "Patient
            noticed a single marble-sized swelling in the right breast 2 months
            ago")</li>
          <li>How long has the lump/swelling been present? (e.g., 2 months)</li>
          <li>Is it constant or intermittent?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>A/R: Aggravating&nbsp;</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Does the lump size or discomfort change with menstrual cycle?</li>
          <ul>
            <li>(e.g., worsens premenstrually in fibrocystic
              changes/fibroadenosis)</li>
          </ul>
          <li>Pregnancy</li>
          <li>lactation</li>
          <li>Hormones</li>
          <li>HRT</li>
          <li>Medicines</li>
          <ul>
          </ul>
          <li>Any specific movements, pressure, or activities that make it more
            prominent or painful?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Relieving Factors:
        <ul>
          <li>Does anything make it smaller or less noticeable (e.g., specific
            positions, post-menstruation)?</li>
          <li>Any effect of simple analgesia if painful?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <br>
      <br>
      <li><strong>C: Character/Type (Patient's description of the lump if they
          can provide it)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>size</li>
          <li>shape</li>
          <li>skin</li>
          <li><br>
          </li>
          <li>Patient's perception of its feel (e.g., hard, soft, rubbery, like
            a pea or grape).</li>
          <li>Is it perceived as a discrete lump or a general area of
            thickening/swelling? (e.g., "vague mass" mentioned in chief
            complaint)</li>
          <li>Pain characteristics if pain is a feature of the lump itself:
            <ul>
              <li>Short duration &amp; Painful: Suggests Inflammatory.</li>
              <li>A bit longer &amp; Painless: Can be Malignant (many breast
                cancers are initially painless).</li>
              <li>Long duration &amp; Less Painful: Can be Chronic Inflammation
                (e.g., some forms of mastitis, duct ectasia).</li>
              <li>Long duration &amp; Painless: Can be Benign (e.g.,
                fibroadenoma, cyst).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>R: Radiation</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Does any discomfort or pain associated with the lump radiate?
            (e.g., to axilla, arm)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>A: Associated Symptoms</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Pain in the lump or breast (see 2nd complaint).</li>
          <li>Nipple discharge (see 3rd complaint).</li>
          <li>Nipple retraction or inversion (see 4th complaint).</li>
          <li>Skin changes over the lump/breast: (Dimpling, puckering, peau
            d'orange, redness, warmth, ulceration, fungation).</li>
          <li>Fever (suggests infection, e.g., mastitis, abscess).</li>
          <li>Other swellings: (e.g., in axilla, supraclavicular fossa
            &acirc;&euro;&ldquo; lymph nodes). (General examples for multiple
            swellings like NF, Diaphyseal Aclasis, Hodgkin's are less specific
            to breast primaries).</li>
          <li>Secondary changes noted by patient: Softening, ulceration,
            fungation, inflammation of the lump.</li>
          <li>Impairment of arm movement on the affected side.</li>
          <li>Disfigurement.</li>
          <li>Systemic symptoms: Unexplained weight loss (Associated with
            Malignancy, TB, AIDS - cold abscess less relevant for typical breast
            primary), fatigue, bone pain.</li>
          <li>Difficulty in respiration, difficulty in swallowing (if advanced
            disease/metastases - rare as initial presentation with lump).</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>P: Progression</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Has the lump changed in size since first noticed? (e.g.,
            "gradually increasing in size and attained present size")
            <ul>
              <li>Very Rapid progression: Suggests Inflammatory.</li>
              <li>Rapidly progressive: Can be Malignant (e.g., some Ca except
                atrophic scirrhous Ca.).</li>
              <li>Slowly progressive: Can be Benign (e.g., Fibroadenosis,
                Fibroadenoma) or some slow-growing cancers.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Has it changed in consistency or other characteristics?</li>
          <li>Regressive (e.g., inflammatory process resolving).</li>
          <li>Static.</li>
          <li>Static then Rapid growth (suggests benign lesion undergoing
            malignant change, though rare for most common benign lumps).</li>
          <li>History of Recurrence (after excision/previous treatment for a
            breast lump):
            <ul>
              <li>Benign lesion recurring.</li>
              <li>Malignant recurrence (local or regional).</li>
              <li>Cyst recurrence if wall incompletely removed.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>P: Pattern</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Is the lump always present?</li>
          <li>Does its size or tenderness fluctuate, e.g., with the menstrual
            cycle (cyclical changes)?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>E: Effect on life</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Impact on daily activities, clothing choice, body image, sleep.</li>
          <li>Any anxiety or concern caused by the lump.</li>
          <li>Interfering with movement.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>R: Red Flags (for the lump itself)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><em>Cancer</em></li>
          <li>Rapid growth.</li>
          <li>Lump in axilla = lumps and bumps elsewhere?</li>
          <li>Weight loss</li>
          <li>Tiredness</li>
          <li>Bone pain</li>
          <li>Associated <strong>skin </strong>changes (puckering, dimpling,
            peau d'orange, ulceration).</li>
          <li>Associated <strong>nipple </strong>changes (new retraction,
            bloody discharge).</li>
          <li>Age &gt;40 years with a new persistent lump.</li>
          <li>(C-MINT approach can be used for differential diagnosis).</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>S: Scale</strong> </li>
      <ul>
        <li>(If associated <strong>pain</strong>, scale 0-10. </li>
        <li>Not usually for the <b><u>lump </u></b>itself unless for "<b><u>bother
              </u><u>score</u></b>").</li>
      </ul>
    </ul>
